CAPE TOWN - The National Credit Regulator says the number of bad loans could rise sharply during the recession.South Africa fell into a technical recession for the first time since 2009 in the first quarter of the year.The credit regulator says indebted consumers are struggling to pay back a cumulative 1-point-7 trillion rand.READ: South Africa is in recession: How do we beat it?It s told parliament that more than a third of the accounts are currently impaired and says this figure may rise.The body has also called on credit providers to lend responsibly during the economic downturn.READ: Economic pain hit ordinary people long before recessionMeanwhile, the treasury has proposed debt amnesty to assist poor and indebted consumers.The Credit monitor has lobbied for more research to determine the impact of debt relief packages on lenders.eNCA